# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# Peridot is the **event-driven BDD test framework
# for PHP** by peridot-php — modern BDD-style testing
# with describe/it syntax similar to Mocha (JavaScript)
# or RSpec (Ruby).  Pivots from Perl Getopt::Long
# (R281 cpanm) into the **PHP language tooling
# cluster**.  Sister to PHPUnit / Pest / Codeception.
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented
# PHP Symfony Console CLI** — adds PHP to the cross-
# language CLI taxonomy (21 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: Peridot uses **Symfony
# Console** library at `Symfony\Component\Console` —
# corpus's **first documented PHP Symfony Console
# CLI**.  `Symfony\Component\Console` is **the** de-
# facto standard PHP CLI library — used by Composer,
# PHPUnit, Laravel Artisan, Symfony Console
# applications, PHP-CS-Fixer, PHPStan, Pint, and most
# other PHP CLI tooling.  Extends the **cross-
# language CLI taxonomy** to TWENTY-ONE library
# variants: Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3), Crystal
# OptionParser (R269), Haskell optparse-applicative
# (R270), OCaml Cmdliner (R271), C POSIX getopt
# (R272), Java picocli (R276), Kotlin clikt (R277),
# Scala decline (R278), Dart args (R279), Ruby
# OptionParser (R280), Perl Getopt::Long (R281),
# **PHP Symfony Console** (R282 — NEW).  **MAJOR
# PATTERN MILESTONE**: 21 cross-language CLI library
# variants documented.  Documents the **class-based
# InputDefinition pattern**:
# ```php
#   class InputDefinition extends Definition {
#     public function __construct() {
#       parent::__construct([]);
#       $this->addArgument(new InputArgument('path',
#         InputArgument::OPTIONAL, 'help'));
#       $this->addOption(new InputOption('focus', 'f',
#         InputOption::VALUE_REQUIRED, 'help'));
#     }
#   }
# ```
# Distinct from Java picocli's `@Annotation` (R276)
# — both are class-based but Symfony's approach uses
# CONSTRUCTOR-METHOD invocation of `addArgument`/
# `addOption` while picocli uses ANNOTATIONS on
# fields.  Documents the **constructor-method-call
# CLI pattern** in PHP — vs Pint's `configure()`
# method pattern (Pint extends Command directly;
# Peridot extends InputDefinition).  Symfony Console
# supports BOTH patterns.
#
# Critical extraction note: Peridot uses **`BITWISE OR`
# combining InputOption value-types** at
# InputDefinition.php:28 — `InputOption::VALUE_REQUIRED
# | InputOption::VALUE_IS_ARRAY` combines TWO flags:
# `VALUE_REQUIRED` (must take a value) AND
# `VALUE_IS_ARRAY` (repeatable, collects into array).
# The default for an IS_ARRAY option is an array
# (`['spec']`).  Documents the **bitwise-OR enum
# combination pattern** in Symfony Console — distinct
# from clap derive's `Vec<T>` field type (R260 dua —
# type-system-driven) and from argparse's `action=
# "append"` (R267 alembic — single keyword arg).
# Symfony's approach is C-style: each value-type is a
# bit flag, OR them together to combine.  Documents
# the **InputOption value-type enum flags**:
#   `VALUE_NONE`      — boolean flag (no value)
#   `VALUE_REQUIRED`  — must take a value
#   `VALUE_OPTIONAL`  — value is optional
#   `VALUE_IS_ARRAY`  — repeatable (combines via |)
#   `VALUE_NEGATABLE` — auto-generates `--no-FLAG`
#                       (newer Symfony Console feature)
# Corpus's **first documented bitwise-OR enum
# combination** in CLI declaration.
#
# Critical extraction note: Peridot uses **Symfony
# Console XML-like style markup in help text** at
# InputDefinition.php:23 — `<comment>(default: *.spec
# .php)</comment>` embeds Symfony Console-specific
# style tags within help strings.  Symfony Console
# renders these as colored/styled output in the
# terminal.  Common tags: `<info>` (green), `<comment>`
# (yellow), `<question>` (cyan), `<error>` (red).
# Custom tags can be defined via `OutputFormatter::
# setStyle()`.  Documents the **inline-style-markup
# pattern** in CLI help text — distinct from clap
# derive's plain strings (R247+) and from picocli's
# `${DEFAULT-VALUE}` / `${COMPLETION-CANDIDATES}`
# template interpolation (R276 checkstyle).  Symfony
# Console is one of the few CLI libraries with
# built-in TERMINAL-STYLED help output.  Corpus's
# **first documented inline-style-markup help pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: Peridot uses **Symfony
# Console's BUILT-IN `--help`, `--version`, `--quiet`,
# `--verbose`, `--ansi`, `--no-ansi`, `--no-interaction`**
# inherited from the Application base class — even
# though Peridot's InputDefinition only declares
# `--help` and `--version` explicitly, the parent
# Symfony Console Application provides several
# globals.  Documents the **inherited-global-flags
# pattern** in class-based CLI libraries — distinct
# from clap derive's auto-`-h/--help` (R247+) and
# Click's `auto_envvar_prefix` (R266 uvicorn).
# Symfony Console's globals are inherited via class
# hierarchy.  Plus Peridot REDECLARES `--help` and
# `--version` at InputDefinition.php:32-33 which
# OVERRIDES the inherited ones with its own short
# alias (`-h`, `-V`).
#
# Critical extraction note: Peridot uses **simple
# `addArgument` / `addOption` chained calls** at
# InputDefinition.php:21-34 — Symfony Console's
# preferred imperative API.  Plus Peridot exposes
# convenience wrapper methods `argument()` and
# `option()` at lines 47-69 that wrap the constructor
# calls.  Documents the **imperative-add API style**
# — Symfony Console supports both: declarative (pass
# array of InputArgument/InputOption to constructor)
# AND imperative (call addArgument/addOption after
# instantiation).  Peridot uses the IMPERATIVE style.
# Plus the convenience wrappers (`argument`/`option`
# methods at lines 47-69) return `$this` for chaining
# — fluent-builder style.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# Peridot reporters built-in list (decoded from
# Peridot's `Reporter\` directory).
local -a reporters=(
  'spec:default; describe/it indented spec output'
  'min:minimal output (just dots and summary)'
  'anonymous:anonymous reporter (no output)'
)

# 11 options + 1 positional decoded source-direct
# from InputDefinition.php at lines 21-34.
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help (declared in InputDefinition)]' \
  '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[show Peridot version]' \
  '(-f --focus)'{-f+,--focus=}'[run tests matching pattern]:pattern:' \
  '(-s --skip)'{-s+,--skip=}'[skip tests matching pattern]:pattern:' \
  '(-g --grep)'{-g+,--grep=}'[run tests with filenames matching pattern (default: *.spec.php)]:pattern:' \
  '(-C --no-colors)'{-C,--no-colors}'[disable output colors]' \
  '--force-colors[force output colors]' \
  '*'{-r+,--reporter=}'[reporter to use (repeatable; VALUE_REQUIRED | VALUE_IS_ARRAY)]:reporter:(($reporters))' \
  '(-b --bail)'{-b,--bail}'[stop on first failure]' \
  '(-c --configuration)'{-c+,--configuration=}'[PHP file containing Peridot configuration]:file:_files -g "*.php"' \
  '--reporters[list all available reporters]' \
  '1:path to directory or file containing specs:_files'
